<div class="patternContent"><div class="patternTopic"> <h1><a name="dCache_Storage_Element_Install_N"></a>  dCache Storage Element Install Notes </h1>
<p />
First, check that the Trash.Trash/Trash/IntegrationDCacheStorageElementPrerequisites are met on your system, and follow the instructions as needed.
<p />
Download the dCache bundle from <a href="http://www.dcache.org/downloads" target="_top">http://www.dcache.org/downloads</a>. You can use the "Linux/Intel rpms tar ball" that contains the dCache Server, Pnfs, Clients, SRM. Unpacking the file (dcache-bundle-1.6.6-1.tgz) creates a directory (dcache-bundle-1.6.6-1), containing the needed rpms.
<p />
Do not follow the instructions in the INSTALL file. Rather, go to the web page <a href="http://www.dcache.org/manuals/Book" target="_top">http://www.dcache.org/manuals/Book</a> and follow the directions there. The dCache Book will be more up-to-date than the INSTALL file. However, read the rest of this page for further modifications which may not be in the dCache Book.
<p />
Whether you need to install postgres or not, follow the link <a href="http://www.dcache.org/manuals/Book/cb-postgres-install.shtml" target="_top">Section 1, "Installing a PostgreSQL Server"</a> from the <a href="http://www.dcache.org/manuals/Book/in-install.shtml" target="_top">Installation of a Basic dCache Instance</a> page to setup the postgres configuration for the rest of the install. See also Trash.Trash/Trash/IntegrationDCacheAdditionalPostgresTips. If you need to install Postgres, see <a href="/bin/view/Main/PostgresInstallRPMS" class="twikiLink">PostgresInstallRPMS</a>.
<p />
If you are installing on Fedora Core 3, Scientific Linux 4, or any OS in which "mount" defaults to NFS version 2, see Trash.Trash/Trash/IntegrationDCacheNFSversion. 
<p />
When editing the file /opt/d-cache/config/dCacheSetup, in addtion to the changes directed by the dCache Book, use the lines
<pre>
   portBase&#61;22
</pre>
and
<pre>
   gsiFtpPortNumber&#61;2811
</pre>
<p />
In /opt/d-cache/etc/node_config, in addtion to the changes directed by the dCache Book, if you have a host certificate use these lines
<pre>
   GSIDCAP&#61;yes
   GRIDFTP&#61;yes
   SRM&#61;yes
</pre>
<p />
You will need to add a user for each VO you will support, for example,
<p />
<pre>
# useradd uscms01
# vi /etc/group
uscms01:x:501:
# vi /etc/passwd
uscms01:x:501:501::/home/uscms01:/bin/bash
</pre>
<p />
If you have set up /etc/grid-security/grid-mapfile and would like to use the script grid-mapfile2dcache-kpwd to create dcache.kpwd, here is a copy: Trash.Trash/Trash/IntegrationDCacheKPWDScipt. The /opt/d-cache/etc/dcache.kpwd file should look something like:
<pre>
version 2.1

# Mappings for &#39;uscms01&#39; users
mapping &#34;/DC&#61;org/DC&#61;doegrids/OU&#61;People/CN&#61;Gerald Holmes 899524&#34; uscms01

# Login for &#39;uscms01&#39; users
login uscms01 read-write 501 501 / / /
        /DC&#61;org/DC&#61;doegrids/OU&#61;People/CN&#61;Gerald Holmes 899524
</pre>
<p />
For firewall configuration, see Trash.Trash/Trash/IntegrationDCacheFirewallSetup.
<p />
<p />
-- <a href="/bin/view/Main/TedHesselroth" class="twikiLink">TedHesselroth</a> - 17 Nov 2005</div><!-- /patternTopic-->
